english:
  title: The Immortal Peach of the Royal Garden
  author: Choi Yu-seon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    A peach tree newly planted in the royal garden—
    transferred here from the Celestial Orchard where immortals dwell.
    Its roots dig deep into the crimson earth of the palace,
    its shadow spreads across the purple courtyard.

    Delicate leaves unfold like brushstrokes on silk,
    thousands of blossoms blaze as if set aflame.
    Highest among the trees of the imperial chancellery,
    its fragrance carries the incense of heaven's altar.

    With the throne so near, spring blooms early,
    and in the clear dawn, pearls of dew crown each flower.
    This peach is surely the gift of the Queen Mother of the West,
    and by its virtue, the sovereign's reign shall stretch ten thousand years.
  footnotes:
    - The Queen Mother of the West (王母) is a legendary figure in Chinese mythology, traditionally associated with immortality and divine gifts.
    - The 'peach of immortality' is a classical symbol of longevity and eternal youth in East Asian tradition.
